Decorator : is a structural design patterns which is to Add new behaviors or enhance functionality dynamically without subclassing.
    Client assembles the wrapper chain
    Multiple decorators stackable

*** Spring and Spring Boot implement the Decorator pattern primarily through dynamic proxies and Aspect-Oriented Programming (AOP), allowing runtime wrapping of beans with additional behaviors like logging or caching without altering core classes.
*** Spring AOP uses JDK dynamic proxies (or CGLIB) to create decorator-like wrappers around beans. Aspects act as decorators, intercepting method calls to add cross-cutting concerns such as transactions, security, or metrics. This stacks behaviors dynamically based on annotations like @Transactional or @Cacheable.
*** Implement BeanPostProcessor to wrap beans post-instantiation.
*** Scoped Proxies: For prototype or request-scoped beans injected into singleton beans, Spring creates proxy decorators (@Scope("prototype", proxyMode = ScopedProxyMode.TARGET_CLASS)) to manage lifecycle and scope mismatches dynamically.
*** Custom Decorator Wiring: Use @Service and ordered @Primary or qualifiers to chain service implementations. For example, wrap a core service with logging or validation decorators in configuration



Implementation: Decorator lets you wrap a coffee object with condiments, adding features at runtime.

Step 1: Define the component interface.
public interface Coffee {
    double cost();
    String description();
}

Step 2: Concrete component (base object).
public class SimpleCoffee implements Coffee {
    public double cost() { return 5.0; }
    public String description() { return "Simple Coffee"; }
}

Step 3: Abstract decorator (holds reference to component).
abstract class CoffeeDecorator implements Coffee {
    protected Coffee coffee;
    public CoffeeDecorator(Coffee coffee) { this.coffee = coffee; }
    public double cost() { return coffee.cost(); }
    public String description() { return coffee.description(); }
}

Step 4: Concrete decorators (add behavior).
class MilkDecorator extends CoffeeDecorator {
    public MilkDecorator(Coffee coffee) { super(coffee); }
    public double cost() { return super.cost() + 2.0; }
    public String description() { return super.description() + ", Milk"; }
}

class SugarDecorator extends CoffeeDecorator {
    public SugarDecorator(Coffee coffee) { super(coffee); }
    public double cost() { return super.cost() + 1.0; }
    public String description() { return super.description() + ", Sugar"; }
}

Step 5: Client usage (stack decorators).
public class DecoratorDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Coffee coffee = new SimpleCoffee();
        System.out.println(coffee.description() + " $" + coffee.cost());  // Simple Coffee $5.0

        coffee = new MilkDecorator(coffee);
        coffee = new SugarDecorator(coffee);
        System.out.println(coffee.description() + " $" + coffee.cost());  // Simple Coffee, Milk, Sugar $8.0
    }
}

*** This builds enhanced objects transparently, following open-closed principle.
